President Barack Obama has proclaimed December 15, 2012, as Bill of Rights Day in the United States. In his proclamation, he highlights the importance of the Bill of Rights, which protects fundamental freedoms such as speech, worship, assembly, and due process. He emphasizes that these freedoms are interconnected and form the foundation of the American promise. The President also acknowledges the Framers' intention to balance the power of the Federal Government with the guarantee of basic civil liberties. He calls upon the American people to continue the work of the Framers in order to build a more perfect Union. The proclamation encourages the celebration of the liberties secured by previous generations and pays tribute to those who have fought for civil rights. It also calls for appropriate ceremonies and activities to mark Bill of Rights Day.